Chain pulling is all about having a steady stream of single mobs (multiples can always be handled) so that your group is always busy killing, without depleting the Healer's mana.  It's simple.  When your group has done sufficient damage on a mob, you disengage and go off to find the next mob.  If you time it right, you will have your new mob back to camp just as your assist melee are done with the first one.  Rinse, repeat.  Here are a few things to help you.<br>
<br>
1.  When you first join a group, give yourself a few pulls to test them out.  Let them know you will start chain pulling after you see what they can do.<br>
2.  It's all about you and the Healer.  Stay in touch with the Healer and only stop when/if he needs you to.  Ask for mana status.<br>
3.  Communicate.  I disagree with the other posters here.  I have a button that lets them know I am looking for something to kill and another one for incoming.  These are level 30 groups.<br>
4.  Don't be afraid to tell that loudmouth Ranger to go and find another group if you are pulling too slow for him.  The only two necessary elements for a group in OT is a tank (you) and a healer.  All others can be replaced.  And with the number of people lfg in OT, it takes about 30 seconds.<br>
5.  Don't stop pulling except for out of mana or afk.  People will get the hang of what you're doing.<br>
6.  Take your time pulling.  Don't let them push you, you end up with adds that way and that breaks the rhythm.  If you need more time to get a single pull, disengage sooner.  You can always tank it solo until they finish off the last one if you come back too soon.<br>
7.  Make sure when you disengage that the mob doesn't follow you...<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
8.  Don't be too far from your group when they finish it off or you won't get experience.  <br>
<br>
Hope this helps.  I really had fun chain pulling in OT and DL and the groups I was with treated me with respect and gratitude.<br>
